<p>The original poem, written by Harivanish Rai Bachchan (1907-2003) in Hindustani, is called आ रही रवी की सवारी · <span dir="rtl">آ رہی روی کی سواری</span>, and comes from the collection निशा निमंत्रण · <span dir="rtl">نشا نمنترن</span> (“Invitation of the night,” 1938). The original is available in Nagari on <a href="http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%86_%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B9%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%BF_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B0%E0%A5%80_/_%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%82%E0%A4%B6%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AF_%E0%A4%AC%E0%A4%9A%E0%A5%8D%E2%80%8D%E0%A4%9A%E0%A4%A8">Kavita Kosh</a>.</p>
<p>I have a friend who enjoys waking up very early and watching the sunrise (sentiments I cannot understand…). I was reminded of this poem during one of our conversations, and decided to translate it — in part to share it with my friend since she does not speak Hindustani, but mostly to procrastinate.</p>
</div>
<pre class="poem">
Here comes the procession of the Sun!

The gilded chariot of newborn sunbeams,
A floral path blooming before it,
Cloud-like attendants clad in gold,
Here comes the procession of the Sun!

The birds are a convoy of minstrels,
Singing paeans into the skies,
As the Army of Stars flees the battlefield,
Here comes the procession of the Sun!

I want to leap up, proclaiming "Victory!"
But I falter when I see—
The illustrious King of the Night, now in tatters…
Here comes the procession of the Sun!
</pre>
